<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> The unanimous <a href="/wiki/House_of_Lords_Judicial_Committee" title="House of Lords Judicial Committee" class="mw-redirect">Law Lords</a> judgment on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-12-08"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="12-08"><a href="/wiki/December_8" title="December 8">December 8</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span> ruled that, under English law tradition, "torture and its fruits" could not be used in court (<a href="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/terrorism/story/0,15935,1662107,00.html" class="external text" title="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/terrorism/story/0,15935,1662107,00.html" rel="nofollow">Torture evidence inadmissible in UK courts, Lords rules</a> by Staff and agencies in <a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a> <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-12-08"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="12-08"><a href="/wiki/December_8" title="December 8">December 8</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span>). But the information thus obtained could be used by the British police and security services as "it would be ludicrous for them to disregard information about a ticking bomb if it had been procured by torture."(<a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4510866.stm" class="external text" title="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4510866.stm" rel="nofollow">Torture ruling's international impact</a> by Jon Silverman <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a> <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2005-12-08"><a href="/wiki/December_8" title="December 8">8 December</a> <a href="/wiki/2005" title="2005">2005</a></span>)</li>
